# Payment Architecture — Orakara

## Overview

Orakara supports five payment methods: `OFFLINE`, `MFS` (mobile financial services, e.g. bKash), `BANK_TRANSFER`, `CARD_PAYMENT`, and `PLATFORM_ESCROW`. The first four are off-platform — Orakara records what was agreed but does not move money. `PLATFORM_ESCROW` is fully on-platform: funds are held and released in tranches against verified proof of milestone completion.

Payment method selection is part of the price negotiation. Neither party can proceed to the contract stage until payment method is agreed alongside price, quantity, and lead time.

---

## Payment Method Negotiation

During the price stage, payment mode is treated as a first-class negotiation dimension alongside price, quantity, and lead time. Each dimension has its own status in `PriceNegotiation`:

```
paymentModeStatus        PriceFieldStatus   — PENDING | COUNTERED | AGREED | FINAL_OFFER_PENDING | ...
paymentModeAwaitingRole  String             — whose response is expected
paymentModeFinalOfferBy  String             — userId if final offer triggered
```

A buyer can propose any payment method in their set of `paymentModesOffered`. A seller can accept, counter with their preferred method, or trigger a final offer. If both parties' `paymentModesOffered` arrays never overlap, the system flags `paymentModeDispute = true` on the eventual `NegotiationFailure` record.

The gate to the contract stage (`isPricePaymentAgreed()`) requires all four dimensions — price, payment mode, quantity, lead time — to be `AGREED`, plus tranche agreement if `PLATFORM_ESCROW` was selected.

